~ 0 XTERM256 256 XTERM~
#g--------------------------------------------------------------------------------#n
#n Innocence Lost RPI#y -#n HELP DATABASE
#g--------------------------------------------------------------------------------#n
Xterm256 colors can be accessed with the ^^ symbol.

The predefined xterm colors are:

   n: no colour (switches colour off)
 
   r: ^rdark red^n                        R: ^Rlight red^n
   g: ^gdark green^n                      G: ^Glight green^n
   b: ^bdark blue^n                       B: ^Blight blue^n
   y: ^ydark yellow^n                     Y: ^Ylight yellow^n
   m: ^mdark magenta^n                    M: ^Mlight magenta^n
   c: ^cdark cyan^n                       C: ^Clight cyan^n
   w: ^wdark white^n                      W: ^Wlight white^n
 
   a: ^adark azure^n                      A: ^Alight azure^n
   j: ^jdark jade^n                       J: ^Jlight jade^n
   l: ^ldark lime^n                       L: ^Llight lime^n
   o: ^odark orange^n                     O: ^Obright orange^n
   p: ^pdark pink^n                       P: ^Plight pink^n
   t: ^tdark tan^n                        T: ^Tlight tan^n
   v: ^vdark violet^n                     V: ^Vlight violet^n
 
 So for example "This is ^^Oorange^^n." will colour the word "orange".  You 
 can add more colours yourself just by updating the switch statement.
 
 It's also possible to explicitly specify an RGB value, by including the four 
 character colour sequence (as used by ColourRGB) within square brackets, eg:
 
    This is a ^^[F010]very dark green foreground^^n.
